Swarm architecture.

A swarm cluster is a set of docker hosts, called nodes, talking to each other, and every node plays one of two roles. A manager runs the orchestrator's control plane. It accepts a-p-i calls like create-service, schedules work, and stores the cluster state, and by default managers also run workloads, though you can prevent that. A worker just runs containers, which swarm calls tasks, as assigned by the managers, and it takes no part in control-plane decisions.

The number of managers should always be odd, one, three, five, or seven, because they use a consensus protocol that needs a majority to make decisions. The cluster tolerates roughly half the managers failing, so three managers survive losing one and five survive losing two, while the worker count is unlimited. Picture a row of manager nodes with one elected leader, and a row of worker nodes beneath them.

Three protocols glue the cluster together. The first is the consensus protocol among managers, which elects a leader and replicates the cluster state, services, tasks, secrets, networks, into a log that every manager holds, with reads being cheap and writes going through the leader. The second is a gossip protocol that every node speaks, which spreads the knowledge of which service has tasks on which nodes and at which addresses, and it powers service discovery and overlay-network membership. And the third is the docker a-p-i itself, which managers expose just like an ordinary daemon, but with extra swarm verbs for services, nodes, stacks, secrets, configs, and overlay networks.
